pr_body:
Fixes #409 

This PR unify the output generation and also adds the functionality to generate a CSV file as the output.

Currently, we can only generate single type at once and that also CSV. 
In Future, we can add functionality to drop a list or tuple of output types. Unification will also help in maintaining and upgrading the code faster and easier.

@terriko I've implemented this approach. But I'm a little nervous and need your guidance to know that is this a right approach?
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 384839893, 'comment_body': "Do we *want* this directory in git? I don't think we need it in version control unless we're storing contents, and I can't imagine that we'd want to store output in the repo.  I'm guessing you did it to avoid having to have directory-making code in output_engine.py but I think we could just prefix the default filename instead of using a directory and more or less achieve the same effect. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 2, 27, 0, 0, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 384841245, 'comment_body': "I know the tests are like this, with the filename and the class name similar-but-different, but we already have VersionSignature.py, so it's not a big deal to have OutputEngine.py.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 2, 27, 0, 4, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 384848911, 'comment_body': 'I'm guessing the point of this to generate a somewhat-unique filename to avoid likely file collisions, but if we never tell the user what output we just wrote, I'm not sure if a `{lengthy numeric string}.csv` is going to be helpful, especially since once you run this more than once you're going to have a series of them.  

Some possible options:
1. Force the user to provide a filename and error if one is not provided (make it the user's problem)
2. Write an info level message so the user at least knows what filename was written
3. Add a prefix to the name so at least it's `output.cve-bin-tool.{numbers}.csv`
4. Use datetime to make a filename that gives you the date/time so at least the latest version is pretty obvious.

I'm thinking maybe 2, 3 *and* 4 would be a good combo here?
```python
self.filename = f"output.cve-bin-tool.{datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d.%H:%m:%S:%f')}.csv"
```
I can't decide if it's worth keeping the miliseconds (%f) in there for slightly reduced collision chance at expense of even longer filename.  We could add a short hash instead, but maybe that's over-thinking it.  I'm guessing if you have filename collisions at this level you should probably be generating your own filenames, so seconds is plenty for a default.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 2, 27, 0, 29, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 384851239, 'comment_body': "Add a log call here to tell the user what the filename was in case it was auto-generated.  You can set something in `__init__` so you know when you generated one and only print it there.  Or equally, you could move the code out of `__init__` and into this function (which might make more sense).

And as I said above, I think we should skip the directory and just make a bare file.  

We might need a check in case the user specifies a file that they can't write to/directory that doesn't exist here.  Python's error should be pretty obvious if it can't open the file, but if we have a check then we can revert to console output or just terminate more nicely.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 2, 27, 0, 37, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 384851711, 'comment_body': "Other than this line, the output in output_cves and output_csv is the same.  What about if we put this line into output_cves and have output_csv call output_cves with an argument?  I don't think anyone will mind having an explanatory line added to the console output here.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 2, 27, 0, 38, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_body:
Changes
------------
**updated banner:** Size reduced 

**example output:**

![Screenshot from 2020-04-28 22-08-30](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29910324/80513767-29a87c80-899d-11ea-878a-83ae11c3f968.png)

Changes
------------
- Refactored output_engine.py to output_engine package
- Added check for filename so now even if the user didn't specify the complete filename it will be fine. Example: earlier ```-o myfile -f html``` will generate a file with name `myfile` but it won't have html as the extension. But now a file with name `myfile.html` will be generated. No change if the user-specified filename with extension.
- updated output_html function to use `collections.Counter` in the generation of analysis_data.
- updated tests for the same
- Fixes #807

@terriko @pdxjohnny - PR is ready for review

pr_title: Divided Report in samller components and updated the output_html function
pr_body:
Changes
-------------
- Renamed folder from `html` to more generic `html_reports`
- divided `base.html` in the templates folder to smaller components like base.html, dashboard.html, row_cve.html, product_cve.html
- Added css folder and static files such as bootstrap.css and main.css
- Added js folder and static files such as pygal, bootstrap, jquery and main.js
- updated the function needed to generate the output(`output_html()`).
  - the function will now generate a single file with all the static files linked inside a single file.

The output generation process is tested with sample data but you can't use the output as of now. I'll file other PR's which will modify cve.db and after that, we will get the data needed to generate the report.

This PR will not affect the tool in any manner because we will not be generating anything as of now and the output_html is disabled for now. The PR can be seen to solve the ISSUE HTML REPORTS | STAGE 1 | TASK2

pr_title: Updated Cvedb.py to store summary data
pr_body:
Updates
------------
- Updated cvedb.py to store the Summary data.
- Removed the urlib2 dependency from cvedb.py

As you can see I'm not fetching anything from the cve.db but I'm storing some data into the cve.db. I have updated the table schema to store the summary of the cve. So that we can later fetch and use that.

pr_body:
Fixes #666 
@pdxjohnny @terriko Please Review.

Changes
------------
- Added HTML report as Output type
- Removed Pygal for graph generation
- Now we are using Plotly python for Generating graphs.
- The problem from Kerberos, curl, libcurl was not discovered with new testing structure from Niraj's PR. So now we are not skipping them. 
- Removed Modulename from the checkers
- Now we store data from the scanner in Named Tuples
- We are now using the "product" instead of "modulename" for testing.
- Updated Example.html
- Also Added Support for searchbar

pr_title: Added Support for custom theme in HTML Reports.
pr_body:
Changes 
------------

- Users can now specify their theme directory to override the current theme.
- Users can either replace the whole theme or can just specify the components they want to overwrite. So users like @anthonyharrison who only want to update a particular part say `main.css` will only have to create their own implementation of `main.css` file and rest of the files will be used as it is.

pr_body:
Fixes: #752 

Changes
-------------

pr_review_comments: [{'comment_id': 444544062, 'comment_body': "Failing on windows only during the test console output.  I'm guessing one of the colours isn't available in the limited windows palette?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 23, 22, 30, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 444792671, 'comment_body': "@terriko rich does not fail on unsupported colours it just skips that. The error was due to the encoding. I found out that open by default opens with `utf-8` encoding but in case of windows, it is 8-bit set characters. So we need to force the encoding.
